<subSubSection id="165A5F566B70031393A01FEA97D52628" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="94AE0D8877F74403DCF1D1910116A2F0" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FAF9337DB9A7E9D19AB2EDF79B0B95E7" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
This new species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="AABFC2781D022EB102D0361298CFA769" genus="I." lsidName="I. albogilvus" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="albogilvus">
<emphasis id="6D5C207FCFD8A79A69F7F2406C164EFC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">I. albogilvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., but can be separated from the latter by the following characters: head largely reddish brown, but face reddish yellow (largely yellow in 
<taxonomicName id="F36D8DAD1F0AC924D6EA8F9AE62EC1A8" genus="I." lsidName="I. albogilvus" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="albogilvus">
<emphasis id="1EA548E578ECD6AC3DE0A8DBD2090D8C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">I. albogilvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); mesoscutum reddish brown (yellow, but lobes with black spot in 
<taxonomicName id="3CD4FBA1625AEF9A11F8AC3D2DF7DB3B" genus="I." lsidName="I. albogilvus" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="albogilvus">
<emphasis id="FCAEB057A7ADA3FDD56B6E9834A764DA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">I. albogilvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); hind wing vein 2-SC+R longer than vein 1r-m (shorter than vein 1r-m in 
<taxonomicName id="BDE95021E2D1489C45B35D518E0F83B1" genus="I." lsidName="I. albogilvus" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="albogilvus">
<emphasis id="ADDE4FA91D785F0243E9B3203FD31D78" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">I. albogilvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); in dorsal view length of eye 3.0 times temple and temples strongly narrowed behind eyes (length of eye 2.6 times temple and temples gradually narrowed behind eyes in 
<taxonomicName id="A26D8235706ECCB6BFEFB7869C70DD19" genus="I." lsidName="I. albogilvus" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="albogilvus">
<emphasis id="3100576B33EB114E2E4F048C4A5F6EF1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">I. albogilvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5241CDC5EEBCC1034E5670E37300BED3" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="description">
<paragraph id="5E2EFB3969622C218FF1699E70597252" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3782A64C8249D1D64F411DC1F808948E" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Holotype, ♀, length of body 9.7 mm, of fore wing 9.1 mm, of ovipositor sheath 5.6 mm.</paragraph>
<caption id="C93821505E8430332EA42C911E3BACB7" doi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404365" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
<paragraph id="FEEEAE1A7CA47E9F3AA14B4EB5CB1B4D" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="C949EAFAE51F516CE4DCF8292C82FA4F" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Figure 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="AE2A6D3359ED0E49BE3681A7CE179127" authorityName="Li &amp; Tang &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Indabracon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Indabracon discolor" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis id="F667C15D4EA492C3A74F74A3A944DA0E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Indabracon discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., ♀, holotype, habitus lateral.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="6BCA3E002113738A659E9FF6B987421F" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="93F6CFF21359FEC2CD19FCDB7679A9CD" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Head.</emphasis>
Antenna with 56 segments; apical antennal segment strongly acute, 1.8 times longer than its maximum width (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2C16D9AB7A8396941E799328E5F4A990" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4l</figureCitation>
); third segment 1.2 and 1.3 times longer than fourth and fifth, respectively, the latter as long as wide; length of maxillary palp 0.8 times height of head; malar suture rather weak, punctate and with short setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="871B812F2958E4E52F3A984A4A7C0A75" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4i</figureCitation>
); clypeus height: inter-tentorial distance: tentorio-ocular distance = 3: 14: 7; clypeus with dense, long setae; eye hardly emarginated (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="38E59EFB7C83156A0E06F317B480D31E" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4g</figureCitation>
); face coarsely rugose, with some striae and long setae laterally (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="195793774A80F27FA3FFBBD7250635ED" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4g</figureCitation>
); eye height: shortest distance between eyes: head width = 22: 18: 39; frons largely smooth except for a few weak punctures, with some sparse short setae and a strong median groove (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C5DF33481306DD40301D75414BC3EEC5" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4h</figureCitation>
); vertex largely smooth except for a few weak punctures, and with some sparse short setae; POL: OD: OOL = 3: 4: 6; length of malar space 1.3 times basal width of mandible; length of eye 3.0 times temple in dorsal view; temples largely glabrous except for a few long setae, and directly narrowed behind eyes (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="77139BB113DD41D2C572BAA1104D8B51" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4h</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D39E9D1B2AEBD7AE06CA44BC2CBEF4F3" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="893A824970FB2707729B9BBBAC83DE20" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Mesosoma.</emphasis>
Length of mesosoma 1.7 times its height (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F03D1B7409053182F2751565B41C8E0D" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4c</figureCitation>
); notauli impressed anteriorly half (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1DA469E44D81802E3B25AE9EA1814EE8" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4d</figureCitation>
); mesoscutum smooth, with sparse long setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0001A7A909B4424442F6B1B882B25C64" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4d</figureCitation>
); scutellar sulcus wide, deep, and with crenulae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EB15F8E3BBCAC343F43380742D75759A" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4d</figureCitation>
); scutellum distinctly convex, moderately densely punctate, and with dense short setae posteriorly; metanotum strongly convex medially, and with a short median carina anteriorly (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DC7591E1BD7A46446EF5BA69576DB0A8" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4d</figureCitation>
); propodeum largely smooth except for a few weak punctures and some crenulae medio-posteriorly, and with sparse setae medially, and dense, long setae laterally (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B10FB945B53FD0E964A8A13CB2810327" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="27D088B445ED79BB6BF3D89F3BE8816B" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="E26815E82A6368624C04AF9AB6F3BF81" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Wings.</emphasis>
Fore wing (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6F5760278EB74264439F3CFB5D92CE32" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4a</figureCitation>
): SR1: 3-SR: r = 29: 26: 4; 1-SR+M strongly angled after arising from 1-M, and 1.5 times longer than 1-M; 2-SR: 3-SR: r-m = 8: 26: 7; CU1b 0.5 times as long as 3-CU1; cu-a weakly postfurcal, and rather weakly bent basally towards base of wing. Hind wing (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E443E2EEF388A6C776482AFCBFEA183A" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4b</figureCitation>
): 1r-m more or less straight; SC+R1: 2-SC+R: 1r-m = 23: 10: 7.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="92287EECD73A48A4E88D307A87344D92" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="BC22D308CD58243312984A467860A4DA" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Legs.</emphasis>
Length of fore femur: tibia: tarsus = 21: 25: 30; length of hind femur: tibia: basitarsus = 33: 50: 18; length of femur, tibia and basitarsus of hind leg 3.7, 8.3 and 6.0 times their maximum width, respectively.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B868E71C67E2EE0AA0A8D192CFE15A32" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="263042DCAA67193AF580F42C03B7C5DC" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Metasoma.</emphasis>
Length of T1 1.1 times its apical width, median area convex and coarsely rugose, lateral areas largely smooth except for with a few striae anteriorly (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FEAFCB81437DA05F58E34D449AF42822" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4j</figureCitation>
); lateral grooves of T1 sparsely crenulate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="55C8E91D3B9D63D71CDD96D36D4A3019" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4j</figureCitation>
); T2 largely coarsely sculptured, but medio-basal area smooth (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="01FFDCFE25E9FAA834DB9C1FA6320120" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4e</figureCitation>
); antero-lateral grooves of T2 strongly developed and crenulate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="739FACD779C865EC7548A2B9893FEE0B" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4e</figureCitation>
); second suture deep and crenulate, wide and straight medially, narrow laterally (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1248F60B760BCD0EE744561B13C11FD8" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4e</figureCitation>
); T3-4 with antero-lateral grooves, and latero-posterior corner medium-sized; T3-5 coarsely sculptured, and with crenulate transverse subposterior groove (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D46604C4577B2D9585F0BF5CA1EBC027" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4e</figureCitation>
); T6-7 largely weakly rugose, and with spare long setae posteriorly; hypopygium acute apically, not reaching level of apex of metasoma; ovipositor sheath 0.6 times as long as fore wing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="36F3DB0C7AB39D6A574927D410C89017" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="48ACC6FC8357654846041D5AC628A1DD" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Colour.</emphasis>
Largely black (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="13C237B4D227A0310F47A76D28C2C90B" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype, habitus lateral." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404365" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">3</figureCitation>
); head and mesosoma largely reddish brown, but antenna, eyes, mandible apically and propodeum black, face reddish yellow (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4391984A8EC503A62D820795233AADC0" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4c, d, g</figureCitation>
); fore femur and tibia somewhat infuscate; T1 whitish yellow (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7E0A037AFA3C09F814ABF915AB0DC70D" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4j</figureCitation>
); wing membrane infuscate, pterostigma and veins dark brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F57AD06F23554972B134359DD56B745C" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Indabracon discolor sp. nov., ♀, holotype a fore wing b hind wing c mesosoma, lateral view d mesosoma, dorsal view e metasoma, dorsal view f hind leg, lateral view g head, front view h head, dorsal view i head, lateral view j first metasomal tergite, dorsal view k scapus outer side, lateral view l apex of antenna m apex of ovipositor, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.76.50794.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/404366" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">4a, b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C4D970381F0DDB83ECC9A56477F949FB" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="9BC58DA774385FCC32B2143091171EA8" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Variation.</emphasis>
Length of body of female 7.3-9.7 mm, of fore wing of female 6.8-9.1 mm, and of ovipositor sheath 2.7-5.6 mm; ovipositor sheath 0.4-0.6 times as long as fore wing; fore femur and tibia sometimes reddish yellow ventrally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
