<subSubSection id="7A2A8C4DB9A0B82BB82433207C9372EE" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="C085BB7E631A6489D8D7E70AD5CFE780" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="50C4F234DEEA820857C327AF87D9E979" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
Named after the T1 whitish yellow, while the remainder tergites black: &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="00FAA7E697B5CFCA53B24A1819E591A9" authorityName="Li &amp; Tang &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Indabracon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="discolor" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discolor">discolor</taxonomicName>
&quot; is Latin for &quot;not of the same color&quot;.
</paragraph>
